  "prompt": "How long can meth be detected through a urine drug screen?",
  "response": "Methamphetamine (meth) can typically be detected in urine for **2-5 days** after the last use.\n\nHowever, several factors can influence this detection window, including:\n\n*   **Frequency and amount of use:** Heavy, chronic users will have a longer detection window compared to occasional users.\n*   **Metabolism:** Individuals with faster metabolisms may eliminate the drug more quickly.\n*   **Hydration:** Drinking plenty of fluids can dilute urine and potentially shorten the detection window, although this is not a reliable method to pass a drug test.\n*   **Kidney function:** Impaired kidney function can slow down the elimination of drugs from the body.\n*   **Physical activity:** Exercise can increase metabolism and potentially shorten the detection window.\n*   **Cut-off level of the test:** Drug tests have different cut-off levels (the concentration of the drug that must be present to trigger a positive result). A lower cut-off level will result in a longer detection window.\n\nIt's important to note that this is a general guideline, and individual results can vary.",
